Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while language models are increasingly adept at surface-level linguistic phenomena, their ability to respect deep semantic constraints—such as those governed by monotonicity and negative polarity item (NPI) licensing—remains poorly understood, especially under systematic generalization. Existing work in NLP evaluation often conflates performance on standard test sets with true generalization, echoing concerns raised in Paper 1 about internal and external validity. I argue that to assess whether models truly understand the *causal* role of monotonicity in licensing NPIs (e.g., "any" appearing only in downward-entailing environments), we must design evaluations that isolate this mechanism from spurious cues. Inspired by clinical research principles, I propose a framework that treats model predictions as outcomes of an implicit causal process, where monotonicity is the treatment variable. By constructing nonce linguistic environments—novel syntactic frames with invented predicates—we eliminate learned lexical biases. Furthermore, integrating causal probing (inspired by Paper 2’s offline probing) allows us to analyze model representations *before* response generation, testing whether the model internally tracks monotonicity shifts. This differs from prior work by not just measuring accuracy but diagnosing *how* and *why* models succeed or fail, using controlled manipulations akin to randomized trials. Unlike ILP-based generalization in Paper 3, which focuses on symbolic rule learning, our approach targets neural models’ implicit reasoning in continuous spaces. The novelty lies in merging distributional remoteness, causal analysis, and systematic syntactic control into a unified paradigm for probing linguistic systematicity.

