  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework to rigorously evaluate whether large language models (LLMs) can systematically generalize the linguistic principle of monotonicity-based negative polarity item (NPI) licensing—specifically, whether they allow NPIs like 'any' only in logically licensed (typically downward-entailing) contexts—when exposed to entirely novel, out-of-distribution constructions. While prior work has tested NPI sensitivity in naturalistic data, these evaluations are confounded by lexical memorization, domain-specific patterns, and spurious correlations. Our approach introduces 'nonce constructions': syntactically valid but semantically novel sentence frames built around invented predicates (e.g., 'to frob', 'a gloop') and quantifiers (e.g., 'every zorb', 'no wick'), ensuring no pre-existing associations exist in training data. These constructions are embedded in both upward-entailing (UE) and downward-entailing (DE) environments, allowing precise manipulation of monotonicity. We then probe model behavior through two complementary lenses: (1) generative consistency—whether the model avoids generating unlicensed NPIs in UE contexts—and (2) causal representational analysis—using intervention-based probing to determine if internal model states causally encode monotonicity information prior to output. Drawing from clinical research methodology (Paper 1), we treat monotonicity as a 'treatment' and measure its causal effect on NPI licensing decisions, controlling for syntactic similarity via matching techniques. Additionally, inspired by PiNose (Paper 2), we train lightweight probing classifiers on frozen model activations from earlier layers to predict monotonicity class, using only synthetic, human-unannotated data generated via grammar rules. Success is not merely high accuracy, but robustness across structurally diverse nonce environments and consistent causal signatures in representations. This method enables disentangling genuine linguistic generalization from superficial pattern matching. If models fail despite high accuracy on standard benchmarks, it reveals a critical gap in systematic reasoning. Conversely, success would provide strong evidence for compositional understanding of logical semantics in LLMs. The broader impact includes a new evaluation paradigm for assessing deep linguistic competence in AI systems, with implications for developing more logically coherent and trustworthy language technologies.",
